post_text:
On Tuesday afternoon, we were informed of a positive COVID case on the opposing team of last Friday night's football game. Out of an abundance of caution, and to give us time to follow all policies and procedures practice was cancelled. The game was reviewed and the State Department of Health's guidelines have been followed to determine that none of our players meet the guidelines for being a close contact and subject to quarantine. At this time we see nothing that impacts practice and games moving forward.

With that being said, after speaking with officials from McEwen and in an effort to err on the side of caution, the decision was made to cancel the football game scheduled for this Friday evening. All ticket reimbursements will be handled at the conclusion of football season.

post_text:
One of the most asked questions we are receiving is "when are we going to start back?"Our goal is to have Stewart County Schools open in August.We want our kids back in classrooms.However we are working on different plans so we can be prepared when the Governor makes a recommendation.We will keep everyone updated as we get information and make decisions.Our hope is that all of our students can safely return at the beginning of the year,and we can return to a sense of normalcy.We love and miss all of our students,teachers and staff! Thank you to our parents and students who have pulled together during this crisis and made the best of an unprecedented situation.
Stay well and see you in August!

--
Mike Craig
Director of Schools
Stewart County

In accordance with the Governor's recommendation, Stewart County Schools will be closing for the remainder of the school year.
Plans for SCHS graduation are being finalized and a date will be announced soon.

Meals will continue to be distributed and enrichment materials will be updated on April 27th.

Information on procedures to pick up personal property, turn in school property and receive final report cards,yearbooks etc.. will be announced in the next two weeks.

We hope everyone stays safe and we look forward to returning to school in August.

Mike Craig
Director of Schools Stewart County

STEWART CO. SCHOOLS CLOSED FRIDAY, FEB. 22. DUE TO POSSIBLE FLOODING.

Director Leta Joiner said county officials were advised today at a National Weather Service Briefing, the possibility of flooding on back roads near creeks and rivers is high. Any amount of rain we get could cause flooding and it is forecast to rain tonight.
***>>>LADY REBELS 1ST ROUND REGIONAL TOURNAMENT<<<***
GAME SCHEDULED FOR TOMORROW NIGHT, FRIDAY, FEB. 22 STILL ON! Start time of 7 pm at SCHS Gym. Unless main roads are impacted they will be playing against #4 Forrest.
LADY REBELS #1 in DISTRICT! GO REBELS!

post_text: Congratulations to our School Resource Officer, Del Morgan. He has been promoted to Sergeant and will be supervisor of our other four school resource officers, Chip Warden (Stewart County Middle School), Tim Morgan (Stewart County High School), Stu Hall (North Stewart Elementary) and David Miller (Dover Elementary). Our school system is fortunate to have an SRO in each of our schools and now we are more fortunate to have an SRO supervisor who will be going to each of the schools to assist. Many school systems have only one SRO for all schools. Stewart County is very fortunate in this respect and we are grateful.

post_text: The Stewart County School System Employees and their family members rode the trolly today in the Christmas parade. Our motto is, Read 20 minutes a day and exercise 30 minutes a day. Several of us exceeded our exercise goal while walking and giving out books in the parade. I know I did. I couldnt catch up with the trolly. We gave out around 550 books. Thank you, Tracy Watson for all of this and a special thank you to Jr. Wallace for pulling the trolly. There are not too many people who would give their time like this. Great parade, City of Dover.

AGAIN TOMORROW:

Our Indian Mound school buses will be followed by Stewart County Deputies the entire bus route. This is Bus #6, Bus #15, Bus #30, Bus #35 & Bus #69 - all serving the Indian Mound area. Please - keep your students inside until the bus stops OR if you meet the bus, please have someone with the students. Please do not leave them standing beside the road alone. We are taking every step possible to keep the students safe. We will all get through this crisis together. We appreciate the hard work of all the law enforcement officers and the assistance they have given to us.

Let's Be Careful Out There!

STATUS OFFICIAL: Due to the intense manhunt going on in the Indian Mound area, we are not going to run the Indian Mound bus routes this afternoon. This is Bus #6, Bus #15, Bus #30, Bus #35 & Bus #69. We feel this is the safest thing for our students and drivers. ALL OTHER BUS ROUTES WILL RUN ON NORMAL SCHEDULE. All students who ride those bus routes (from SCHS & SCMS) will be taken to North Stewart Elementary for parent pick up at that location. School officials will stay at North Stewart until each student has been picked up. USE CAUTION and Let's Stay Safe Out There!

ALSO - those High School students who drive to the high school AND live in the Indian Mound area will need parent permission to be released. Only those students in the Indian Mound area.

post_text:
All Stewart County Schools are currently on soft lockdown until the situation with the fugitive is resolved. Today, during school dismissal, all loading areas will have heightened security. Buses that serve the Indian Mound area will be transporting all students to North Stewart Elementary School. Parents or anyone on a student's emergency card must have a photo ID to pick up a student. Students will be escorted from the school by school personnel to their ride. The buses impacted are numbers 6, 30, 69, 35 and 15.
Students who drive from the Indian Mound area will need parent permission to be released at 2:45. Please call Stewart County High School at 931-232-5179 and speak to school administration.

post_text:
Teachers,

I want to take a moment to express my sincere appreciation for the jobs you do. Teaching is not an easy job and in recent years, the job has only become more difficult. I know there are days you question why anyone would want to do what you do. At the end of the day, you are where you are because you have big hearts and love children. You love to see them grow and learn. You want to make a positive difference in their lives. As a former teacher, I realize there is no better feeling than having a former student come up to me and say, "you helped me, you made a difference in my life, I appreciate what you did for me."

Please know I am thankful for you and the wonderful jobs you do. Our students are in the best hands.

HAPPY TEACHER APPRECIATION DAY. You are the best,

Leta Joiner
Director of Stewart County Schools

As a former teacher, I realize there is no better feeling than having a former student come up to me and say, "you helped me, you made a difference in my life, I appreciate what you did for me."

Please know I am thankful for you and the wonderful jobs you do. Our students are in the best hands.

HAPPY TEACHER APPRECIATION DAY. You are the best,

Leta Joiner
Director of Stewart County Schools

post_text: Rumors continue to cause speculation throughout the county as to events that supposedly took place at Stewart County High School on Friday. I want to assure everyone there is not a threat to the safety of the students, teachers, and staff. No weapons, guns or ammunition have been found. No hit list has been uncovered. Nothing is being covered up by school officials. Any findings of a threat, gun, weapon, or ammunition will be shared completely with the public. Law enforcement along with school administration have thoroughly investigated each allegation and there is no credible threat. If you have any questions, concerns or information please contact Leta Joiner at the Stewart County Board of Education at 232-5176. Thank you.

post_text: After receiving a telephone call from Dr. Lee and consulting with other medical professionals in our county, the decision has been made to close schools the remainder of this week. Flu again in on the upsurge and in some cases with life-threatening consequences. This decision is not made lightly, but always with the best interest of students in mind. This closure will cause us to use one additional stockpile day over those designated as stockpile days. Therefore, to make up this additional day, all Stewart County Schools will be in session on President's Day, Monday, February 19, 2018.
